\v 7 Now Mordekai was taking care of his cousin, who was an orphan. When her father¦229093 and mother had died, Mordekai had adopted¦229104 her as his own daughter¦229087. Her¦229102 \add Hebrew\add* name was Hadassah¦229084, and her \add Persian\add* name was Esther. Esther was now a young¦229095 woman¦229095 and she was exceptionally attractive.
\p
\v 8 So¦229109 when the king's command and decree became known, many young¦229116 women were being brought into the capital city of Shushan¦229120 and placed under Hegai's charge, and this is what happened to Esther¦229127. (Hegai was the overseer of the women.)
\v 9 Hegai was very impressed with Esther, and he treated her favourably¦229143. He quickly¦229145 arranged for Esther to receive her beauty¦229148 treatments and her allotment of food, as well as choosing seven¦229155 female servants from the king's palace¦229161 and assigning¦229158 them to be her personal attendants. He also moved Esther and her attendants to the best rooms in the harem for virgins.
\v 10 (Esther¦229174 hadn't revealed her family ties or her Jewishness to anyone, because Mordekai had instructed¦229183 her not to.)
\p
\v 11 Every day Mordekai would walk¦229195 around in front¦229196 of the courtyard¦229197 of the women's¦229200 harem to find out \add from others\add* how Esther¦229205 was doing and how she was being treated.
\p
\v 12 Each young¦229213 woman¦229213 would get twelve months of beauty¦229233 treatment¦229233 according to the \add Persian\add* law for women—there would be six months of applying oil of myrrh¦229237, then six months of perfumes¦229240 and other lotions \add designed for\add* women. Then¦229211 their¦229233 turn would come, one at a time, to be taken to King Ahasuerus¦229220.
