\v 23 When the matter¦229485 was investigated¦229475 and \add the facts\add* discovered, both conspirators were impaled on \add sharpened wooden\add* poles, and in the presence of the king¦229488, the incident was recorded in the royal record of events.
\c 3
\s1 Haman plans to annihilate the Jews
\rem /s1 Haman's Plot against the Jews; Haman Plots to Destroy the Jews; Haman Undertakes to Destroy the Jews; Haman's Plot to Destroy the Jews
\p
\v 1 Some time later, King Ahasuerus¦229497 promoted Haman, one of his officials (and the son of Hammedatha¦229503 \add who was a descendant\add* of Agag). The king¦229496 gave Haman a very important position¦229509—more important than any of his other officials.
\v 2 Then¦229517 the king commanded¦229531 that all his other officials had to bow down in front of Haman to honour him, and they were doing this at the king's gate, except for Mordekai who refused to bow down to reverence Haman.
\v 3 “Why¦229552 are you¦229550 disobeying the king's command¦229553?” asked the other royal servants¦229542 at the king's gate.
\v 4 Mordekai told them that it was because he was a Jew \add (and Jews only worship Yahweh)\add*. He didn't listen¦229563 to their \add warnings\add* so they told Haman¦229566 about it to see¦229567 if he would tolerate¦229568 Mordekai in keeping refusing to bow down.
\v 5 When Haman saw¦229580 that Mordekai would not bow down to him or show him reverence, he was furious.
\v 6 But¦229593 Haman despised the idea of just punishing Mordekai because he'd been told that Mordekai \add didn't bow to him because\add* Mordekai was a Jew. So¦229593 Haman¦229609 decided to annihilate all of Mordekai's people, i.e., all the Jews throughout the kingdom¦229619 of Ahasuerus¦229620.
\p
\v 7 In early April of the twelfth year of King Ahasuerus' reign, Haman¦229640 got his servants to throw¦229635 dice \add to select the best month and the best day to kill the Jews\add*, and the 13th of March was chosen.
\p
\v 8 Then Haman¦229656 \add went to\add* King Ahasuerus¦229658 and said, “\add Your Majesty,\add* there¦229659 is a certain group of people who live among¦229665 the other peoples in every province¦229668 of your empire. They have their¦229670 own set of laws, so they don't¦229682 obey your laws. It's not good for you to allow them to continue to live in your empire.
\v 9 Your majesty, if you approve of this plan, then write a decree saying that all of the Jews must be destroyed¦229694. \add When they're dead, we can take all of their¦229694 possessions, and¦229695 from that\add* I will give 300 tons of silver¦229699 to your administrators for them to put into your royal treasuries¦229709.”
\p
\v 10 \add This seemed sensible to\add* the king so he removed his signet ring from his finger and he gave¦229719 it\f + \fr 3:10 \ft Having the king's signet ring enabled Haman to stamp the king's seal (like a signature) onto the newly drafted laws.\f* to Haman (the son of Hammedatha¦229723, the Agagite¦229724, the adversary of the Jews).
\v 11 The king¦229729 told Haman¦229730, “You can keep the money¦229731 for yourself, and you can do whatever you want to do with those people¦229734.”
\p
\v 12 On the thirteenth day¦229747 of that same month¦229743, Haman called in the royal scribes, and he dictated a letter to them. He told them to send copies to the royal officials¦229771, the governors¦229762 of each province, and the leaders of each people group \add within the empire\add*. The scribes translated the letter so it could be sent to each province using its own alphabet and to each people group in its own language¦229779. To show that he was sending the letter under the king's own authority, Haman sealed¦229784 each copy of the letter with the ring that had the king's official seal on it.
\v 13 Couriers delivered the letters to the officials in every province¦229796 in the empire. The letters said to completely destroy¦229798 all the Jews, including the children and women¦229811, on a single day. That was to be the thirteenth day of March early in the following year. The letters also stated that those who killed the Jews could take everything that belonged to them.
\v 14 The letter told the officials to display¦229835 copies where everyone could see them—that way all the people¦229838 in every single province¦229833 would know that the king had commanded this, and¦229834 they could get ready¦229840 for when the day¦229841 came.
\p
\v 15 So couriers¦229844 hurried¦229846 off with the letters as the king had commanded¦229847. A herald in the capital city¦229857 of Shushan also proclaimed what the letters said. Then the king and Haman¦229854 relaxed and drank together, but there was \add total\add* confusion¦229859 in Shushan \add about how all of this would work out\add*.
\c 4
