\p That idea sounded good to Haman¦230558, so he got the pole erected.
\c 6
\s1 The king honours Mordekai
\rem /s1 Haman executed; The King Honours Mordecai; Mordecai Honoured
\p
\v 1 That¦230570 night¦230563 the king was unable to sleep¦230566 so he ordered the royal chronicles to be fetched and to be read to him.
\v 2 The chronicles mentioned that Bigthan¦230588 and Teresh¦230589, two of the royal guardians¦230593 who protected the doorway to the king's private quarters, had planned to assassinate the king, but that Mordekai had reported it.
\v 3 “What honour¦230607 or recognition did I give Mordekai for saving my life?” the king asked.
\p “Nothing was done for him,” replied the young¦230614 men who were attending¦230616 him.
\p
\v 4 At that moment, Haman¦230627 had entered the outer¦230633 courtyard of the king's house¦230630. He had come to tell the king that he wanted to execute Mordekai on the pole that he'd had set up for him.
\p “Who's out in the courtyard?” the king asked.
\p
\v 5 “Haman's¦230653 out there¦230652 standing¦230654 in the courtyard¦230655,” replied the young men.
\p “Bring him in then,” the king instructed.
\p
\v 6 When Haman came in, the king asked him, “What should I do for a man that I would really like to honour?”
\p Haman thought to himself, “Surely it must be me that the king would like to honour more than anyone else?”
