\rem /s1 The triumphant Jews destroy their enemies
\p
\v 3 Then Esther¦231148 came to speak to the king again¦231147, and she knelt down and put her face right on top of his feet. She cried as she begged him to stop Haman's¦231163 terrible plan to destroy the Jews.
\v 4 The¦231180 king held out his golden scepter¦231177 toward Esther¦231175, so she stood¦231181 up and waited facing the king.
\v 5 “Your majesty,” she said¦231185, “if you think that it's the right¦231197 thing to do, and¦231192 if you're pleased with me, please write a new letter revoking¦231205 the letters¦231208 that Haman¦231210 (the son of Hammedatha¦231213, the Agagite¦231214) sent out \add instructing the people\add* to destroy¦231217 all the Jews throughout your empire.
\v 6 I couldn't bear to see the terrible thing that is about to happen to my people¦231237. I \add certainly\add* couldn't bear to see \add all\add* my relatives destroyed¦231241!”
\p
\v 7 Then king¦231246 Ahasuerus¦231247 said¦231245 to Queen Esther and to Mordekai the Jew, “Listen, I've given¦231256 the house¦231253 of Haman¦231255 to Esther, and they've executed him on the pole because he attempted to destroy the Jews.
\v 8 But¦231271 as you \add both\add* know, no one can revoke¦231296 a letter that has my name and my official seal on it. So¦231271 this is what you should do: write¦231272 \add a new letter\add* to help the Jews¦231275, as you think best and put my name on it and seal the letter with my signet ring.”
\p
\v 9 It was now June, and the king¦231301 sent for his scribes and they wrote a letter to the Jews containing everything that Mordekai dictated. It was also addressed to royal officials¦231328, and to the governors¦231327 and leaders in each province. The empire had 127 provinces, extending all the way from India¦231332 \add in the east\add* to Ethiopia¦231335 \add in the west\add*. The scribes wrote to every province using its own alphabet and to each people group in its own language, and to the Jews in their language and using their alphabet.
\v 10 The letters were written in King Ahasuerus' name, and \add each one\add* was sealed¦231356 with the king's signet¦231357 ring. Then¦231352 the letters were distributed by mounted¦231363 couriers¦231362 riding on swift horses¦231365 bred from the royal¦231366 mares.
\p
\v 11 The letters stated that the king permitted¦231371 the Jews in each and every¦231391 city to get together and defend¦231382 themselves, and what's more to destroy¦231386, kill¦231386, and annihilate¦231388 all the forces of any people¦231394 or province¦231395 hostile to them, including women¦231399 and children, and \add then\add* to plunder¦231401 their possessions.
\v 12 \add This was to take place\add* on a certain day in every province¦231407 throughout the empire: the 13th of March\x + \xo 8:12: \xt 3:7.\x* \add (the same day on which Haman's law was to take effect)\add*.
\v 13 A copy of the decree was to be included as law in every province¦231427 and to be displayed¦231429 to all the people¦231432 so that the Jews could be prepared to fight back against their¦231441 enemies¦231441 on that day¦231438.
\v 14 So the couriers¦231443 on the royal¦231446 horses¦231445 rode out quickly under the king's orders to deliver the letters. The new law was also proclaimed throughout the capital city of Shushan¦231454.
\p
\v 15 The king¦231462 \add gave\add* Mordekai royal¦231464 clothing that was blue and white¦231466, with a large gold¦231468 crown¦231467, and a purple¦231472 robe¦231470 made from fine linen¦231471. The people of Shushan¦231474 cheered happily when Mordekai exited \add the palace\add*.
