\v 17 In every single province¦231487 and in every single city, wherever¦231494 the letter announcing the king's decree was brought, the Jews were very cheerful¦231501 and had big celebrations. Many people¦231507 from other groups in the empire became afraid of the Jews, so they \add converted to Judaism\add* themselves.
\c 9
\s1 The Jews destroy their enemies
\rem /s1 The Jews Destroy Their Enemies; Triumph of the Jews; The Victory of the Jews; Destruction of the Enemies of the Jews
\p
\v 1 \add Finally\add* when the 13th of March arrived, it was time for everyone to do what the letters from the king said that he had decreed for them to do. The enemies of the Jews had expected to destroy the Jews on that day but just the opposite happened—instead, it was the Jews who destroyed their¦231549 enemies.
\v 2 Throughout the empire, the Jews joined together in their¦231571 cities¦231553 to defend themselves against those who wanted to harm them. No one was able to fight back against them because everyone¦231563 \add else\add* in the empire had become afraid of them.
\v 3 All the leaders in each province¦231581, the royal officials¦231580, the governors¦231583, and everyone who worked for the king¦231587 helped the Jews because they had become afraid of Mordekai
\v 4 because he was \add now\add* a very important royal official, and his fame spread throughout the provinces¦231610 as he became more and more powerful¦231616.
\v 5 So the Jews took their weapons and fought against all of their enemies and completely destroyed¦231628 them. They were able to do everything that they¦231631 wanted to do against their enemies.
\p
\v 6 In the capital city of Shushan, the Jews killed¦231635 500 men
\v 7 including \add Haman's ten sons\add* Parshandatha¦231644, Dalphon¦231647, Aspatha¦231650,
\v 8 Poratha¦231654, Adalia¦231657, Aridatha¦231660,
