\v 11 At the end of the day¦231691, the king¦231699 received a report about how many people the Jews had killed¦231695 in the capital city of Shushan¦231696
\v 12 and he told Queen Esther¦231704, “Here in the capital city of Shushan¦231706 the Jews have killed 500 men, including Haman's¦231718 ten sons¦231716. In the rest of my empire, they must have killed many more than that! So tell me what else you want and I'll do it for you. I'll do whatever you ask, so do tell me.”
\p
\v 13 “If it seems like a good¦231742 plan to you, your majesty,” Esther¦231736 replied, “then please allow the Jews who live here in Shushan¦231749 to do again tomorrow¦231746 what you allowed them to do today. Also, command that the bodies of Haman's¦231757 ten¦231754 sons¦231755 be impaled on the wooden pole.”
\v 14 Then¦231763 the king¦231764 ordered for this to be done and a decree was made throughout in Shushan¦231769, and they \add publicly\add* impaled \add the bodies of \add* Haman's¦231774 ten¦231771 sons¦231772.
\v 15 So¦231777 the next day¦231784 on the 14th, the Jews in Shushan gathered¦231777 together again and killed¦231789 300 \add more\add* men in Shushan. But¦231777 \add once again\add* they¦231796 did not take the things that belonged to those men.
\p
\v 16 The Jews in the other parts of the empire, who had gathered together to fight for their lives¦231811 had defeated their enemies and killed¦231814 75,000 of them. But¦231801 they \add too\add* did not take the things that had belonged to their enemies.
