\s1 The celebration named ‘Purim’
\rem /s1 The Festival of Purim; The feast of Purim
\p
\v 20 Now Mordekai recorded¦231890 everything that had happened and sent¦231896 letters¦231897 to all the Jews throughout the empire, in both the near provinces¦231906 and the far away ones.
\v 21 That decree established an annual holiday on the 14th and 15th of March every year,\f + \fr 9:21 \ft The OET-RV gives an approximate time of the year in our calendars, but the Jewish calendar is largely a lunar calendar so the dates of the feast in our calendars moves around a little. In 2024 for example, ‘Purim’ begins on the evening of March 23 in Israel and concludes at sundown on March 24.\f*
\v 22 because those were the days when the Jews no longer \add had to oppose\add* their enemies¦231939 and that was the month¦231940 when their sorrow¦231944 and mourning¦231946 had changed¦231942 into a good day. Now they were instructed to make them days of feasting¦231952 and happiness, and sending¦231954 of gifts¦231958—to each other but also to the needy.
\v 23 The Jews had already celebrated those days that way, so they¦231966 \add readily\add* agreed to do what Mordekai had written¦231971.
\p
\v 24 Yes, Haman¦231976 (the son of Hammedatha¦231979, the Agagite¦231980), the enemy of all the Jews, had plotted to annihilate them, and he had thrown¦231990 a ‘Pur’ (which is ‘lot’ or perhaps ‘dice’) \add choose the date\add* to crush¦231994 them and to destroy them.
\v 25 But¦231997 \add instead they would remember how Queen Esther stood\add* in front¦231998 of the king¦231999, and how he had said¦232000 in the letter, “Let his evil¦232006 plot that he plotted concerning the Jews return¦232004 on his head, and let them execute him and his sons¦232020 on the pole.”
\v 26 Therefore they called¦232028 this celebration ‘Purim¦232031’\f + \fr 9:26 \ft Plural of Hebrew ‘Pur’ meaning ‘lot/dice’.\f* because of what they had experienced and because of the contents of \add Mordekai's\add* letter¦232044.
\v 27 The Jews agreed to establish those two days as holidays and to observe¦232075 them on those specific days as they'd been instructed. They agreed that they and their¦232066 descendants¦232066 and everyone who became part of the Jewish people would celebrate it every year.
\v 28 So¦232087 that's why every Jewish family¦232096 in every generation¦232093 \add since\add* has celebrated these days as holidays, wherever they live. The Jewish community and its descendants¦232112 will always faithfully observe this festival of ‘Purim’.
\p
\v 29 Then Queen Esther¦232116 (the daughter¦232118 of Abihail¦232120), with \add help from\add* Mordekai the Jew, wrote¦232115 a second¦232133 letter¦232130 about ‘Purim’.
\v 30 He sent¦232135 this \add second \add* letter¦232136 to all the Jews throughout the empire of King Ahasuerus¦232149, with words¦232150 of peace¦232151 and¦232145 truth¦232152
\v 31 to set up the ‘Purim’ celebration on the given dates according to what Mordekai the Jew and Queen Esther¦232166 had determined for them. \add They also confirmed\add* that the Jews should continue the times¦232160 of fasting¦232177 and mourning that they¦232169 had established¦232154 for themselves and their¦232172 future descendants¦232175.
